caption:
Meet Miguel Cesar Bautista, an Engineering Manager here at Coursera!

“I enjoy breaking down walls, opening doors and windows, and making the connections my team needs to get work done,” Miguel says.

If you’ve used our mobile app, you’ve likely seen his and his team’s work. He’s also active in our internal community and is lauded for making time to engage and contribute to our annual Make-a-Thon (MAT)—a competitive sprint week for passion projects Courserians believe will make Coursera better for everyone.

👫 Miguel’s key skill: “The most powerful tool in this line of work is empathy. Software engineering can be isolating and cerebral. And while assistive (AI) tools are growing, the best software still comes from the alchemy of engineering teams. Train your empathy muscles, and use them often. Be empathetic to both your end user and your programming buddy.”

💼 His management theory: “I’m not a good gardener, but the analogy fits: While I’m occasionally ‘in the weeds,’ my value to the team is holistic. I make sure the lawn is easy to maintain. If individuals are the plants and flowers, I need to know which need more water or sun. I also help ensure our lawn can sit beside other well-groomed ones in Coursera’s engineering village.”

🎨 On staying creative: “It feels like sorcery watching my team do good work. MAT unlocks the creative force behind individuals from design, sales, engineering, marketing, accounting—you name it—and lets them just make and be and do cool things,” Miguel says. “Creativity is what makes us ‘more human than human.’ MAT helps you access that feeling and harness it in the future.”

Miguel’s latest creative venture? 3D printing! “Several University of Illinois Urbana-Champaign courses helped me get my feet wet before diving in,” he says. Check them out at the link in bio!

caption:
Meet Sandra Ximena Delgado Betancourth, a Principal Learning Design Consultant here at Coursera!

“I work closely with product, engineering, and design teams to shape how Coursera uses AI to support real learning,” she says. She’s helped shape features like Coach and Dialogues. “What I enjoy most is seeing how pedagogy plays a central role in how we build. It’s exciting to bring learning science into the heart of ed-tech innovation.”

🛠️ In her skills toolkit: “I rely on learning science, experimentation, prompt design or prompt engineering, and cross-functional collaboration. Also, I use data to understand what’s working and why. I’ve developed these skills through a mix of academic training, hands-on work, iteration, and (of course) many online courses.”

🎨 On participating in Make-a-Thon, Coursera’s annual sprint week reserved for passion projects: “It’s one of my favorite parts of being a Courserian. It gives me the space to stretch beyond the day-to-day, think boldly, and build something new and unique. It’s a reminder that innovation is a team sport, and it takes a lot of collective creativity, the freedom to reimagine, and the courage to try things that might not work (yet!).”

🔮 Her advice for her younger self: “Your path doesn’t have to be conventional to be meaningful. Unconventional, unique paths can be a strength, even if they don’t fit neatly into a job description. What’s really important, above all, is to keep learning. Learning is your edge and your superpower.”

Sandra’s current learning adventure? University of Alberta’s Software Product Management Specialization! “I use Coursera Coach a lot when learning, asking questions, testing my understanding, for me it goes full circle, to be able to use and test the products that I helped build.” Join her by clicking the link in bio.

caption:
Meet Dennis Harlow, a December 2024 graduate of the @illinois1867 @giesbusiness iMSA 👋

Through his career in commercial banking, Dennis discovered his passion for accounting and helping businesses succeed. With a new professional purpose, he enrolled in the Gies iMSA to gain the skills he needed to support his next chapter.

🧠 Know what matters: After exploring other programs, Dennis homed in on his non-negotiables. “After not being in school for 20+ years, I knew I wanted something with groupwork, interaction, and a strong connection with the school. After choosing Gies, it was within a week that I was like ‘Oh my gosh this is amazing.’” 

🏋️ Flexible and sustainable : Integrating his learning into his full-time work schedule made all the difference for Dennis. “The flexibility of the program helped me balance work and school. Plus, the professors were hilarious and engaging. They made even the driest material dynamic and exciting.”

🌱  Build your network: Community and collaboration were important for Dennis during his journey through the program. “The wonderful thing about the University of Illinois and the Gies program is that they try to keep you together and connected with the school. We help each other. It’s a very cohesive community, and it truly felt like family.”

caption:
From Chemistry to Strategy: Meet Ishpinder Kailey, a 2023 graduate of the online Gies iMBA! 👋

A PhD in physical chemistry, two master’s degrees in science and engineering, and a passion for STEM were just the beginning for Ishpinder. With lofty business goals and a drive to expand her impact, she took her education a step further. “I chose an MBA because I wanted to understand the strategic and financial decisions behind the work I was already doing. I knew the industry, I just needed the tools to do more with that knowledge.”

🏋️ Resilience meets real-world learning: After losing her husband and taking on the role of single parent, Ishpinder persevered, knowing she could be a positive example for her twin daughters. “I come from a middle-class family in India. Whatever I accomplish, I know it’s because I really worked hard. I want my daughters to remember that I tried. I don’t want them to think I had a chance and didn’t take it. Execution is my strength. Most people lack execution.”

👫 The power of community: Having accomplished so much on her own, Ishpinder leaned into the collaborative environment her program fostered. “It’s been transformational. The professors are exceptional, and the peer learning from a global cohort is a tremendous asset. I particularly valued the emphasis on collaboration and strategic thinking.”

🌱 There’s no expiration date for growth: “It’s never too late to try. If you’re not trying, you’re already a failure. I started my MBA in my early forties, and I always tell myself, it’s never too late to try.”
